Note: Elixir Semantic Analyzer for Translation Translation System
Note: Handles Elixir's actor model, pattern matching, OTP behaviors, and metaprogramming

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/elixir/elixir_parser.runa" as ElixirParser
@Reasoning:
The analyzer is the single mutable context threaded through every recursive AST visit; bundling all per-analysis state (module/function cursors, pattern bindings, actor registry, OTP behavior map, error/warning accumulators) into one struct lets the visitor restore prior state on exit without an explicit stack and keeps cross-cutting concerns (supervision tree, ETS usage, protocols) addressable from any visit site.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Fields are typed Integer because they hold opaque pointers into Runa-side dictionaries and lists allocated via memory_allocate; that uniform handle representation lets the visitor functions accept any container without overloads. current_module and current_function are saved-and-restored across recursive analyze_* calls so nested module/function scopes do not corrupt outer state.
@End Implementation
Type called "ElixirSemanticAnalyzer":
    symbol_table as Integer  Note: Module and function scope tracking
    current_module as Integer  Note: Current module being analyzed
    current_function as Integer  Note: Current function being analyzed
    pattern_context as Integer  Note: Pattern matching variable bindings
    actor_processes as Integer  Note: Map of spawned processes
    genserver_state as Integer  Note: GenServer state analysis
    supervisor_tree as Integer  Note: Supervision hierarchy
    otp_behaviors as Integer  Note: OTP behavior compliance
    protocol_implementations as Integer  Note: Protocol implementations
    macro_definitions as Integer  Note: Macro definitions and expansions
    metaprogramming_context as Integer  Note: Compile-time code generation
    error_list as Integer  Note: Semantic errors
    warning_list as Integer  Note: Semantic warnings
    process_registry as Integer  Note: Named process registry
    ets_tables as Integer  Note: ETS table usage
    message_protocols as Integer  Note: Message passing protocols
End Type

@Reasoning:
A semantic Elixir module is more than a name and function list: OTP behavior membership, supervision strategy, protocols, structs, and use/import/alias dependencies all influence later semantic checks (callback completeness, supervision tree shape, protocol dispatch). Recording them on the module record lets validate_otp_behavior_compliance and analyze_supervision_tree work without re-walking the AST.
@End Reasoning
Type called "ElixirSemanticModule":
    name as String
    attributes as Integer  Note: Module attributes (@moduledoc, @doc, etc.)
    functions as Integer  Note: Public and private functions
    macros as Integer  Note: Macro definitions
    protocols as Integer  Note: Protocol definitions
    implementations as Integer  Note: Protocol implementations
    structs as Integer  Note: Struct definitions
    otp_behavior as String  Note: OTP behavior if any
    supervision_strategy as String  Note: If supervisor module
    dependencies as Integer  Note: use, import, alias, require
End Type

@Reasoning:
Elixir functions are multi-clause with guards, and pattern variables bound in one clause are scoped to that clause only; the semantic record therefore carries clauses, guards, and pattern_variables together so exhaustiveness, redundancy, and binding leakage can be checked locally. otp_callback is captured to flag deviations between callback signatures and behavior contracts (e.g., handle_call/3 arity).
@End Reasoning
Type called "ElixirSemanticFunction":
    name as String
    arity as Integer
    clauses as Integer  Note: Function clauses for pattern matching
    guards as Integer  Note: Guard expressions
    visibility as String  Note: "public" or "private"
    otp_callback as String  Note: OTP callback type if any
    pattern_variables as Integer  Note: Variables bound in patterns
    return_patterns as Integer  Note: Possible return value patterns
    side_effects as Integer  Note: List of side effects
End Type

@Reasoning:
Elixir processes form a graph (links and monitors) and an inheritance tree (supervision); modeling each spawn site with linked_processes, monitored_by, and supervision_info lets downstream checks detect orphan processes, missing trap_exit handlers, and unsupervised long-lived actors without re-traversing the AST.
@End Reasoning
Type called "ActorProcess":
    spawn_location as Integer  Note: AST node where spawned
    process_type as String  Note: "spawn", "Task", "GenServer", etc.
    message_protocol as Integer  Note: Expected message types
    linked_processes as Integer  Note: Linked processes
    monitored_by as Integer  Note: Monitoring processes
    supervision_info as Integer  Note: Supervisor information
End Type

@Reasoning:
Construction zeros every container by allocating fresh dicts/lists rather than sharing module-level state, which prevents cross-analysis bleed when the same compiler invocation analyzes multiple Elixir source files. initialize_elixir_builtins is called here so users never see "undefined GenServer" against the standard library.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Each container field is initialized via create_dict or create_list which call memory_allocate; the analyzer struct is returned by value but Runa's struct semantics carry the heap pointers, so the caller owns the analyzer lifetime and is responsible for releasing it once the file has been fully analyzed.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_elixir_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Elixir semantic analyzer instance

    Let analyzer be a value of type ElixirSemanticAnalyzer with
        symbol_table as proc create_dict,
        current_module as 0,
        current_function as 0,
        pattern_context as proc create_dict,
        actor_processes as proc create_dict,
        genserver_state as proc create_dict,
        supervisor_tree as proc create_dict,
        otp_behaviors as proc create_dict,
        protocol_implementations as proc create_dict,
        macro_definitions as proc create_dict,
        metaprogramming_context as proc create_dict,
        error_list as proc create_list,
        warning_list as proc create_list,
        process_registry as proc create_dict,
        ets_tables as proc create_dict,
        message_protocols as proc create_dict

    Note: Initialize built-in Elixir/OTP modules and functions
    proc initialize_elixir_builtins from analyzer

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
This is the central visitor dispatch. Using a Match on node_type instead of a polymorphic vtable keeps the dispatch tight and lets the type tags imported from ElixirParser stay the single source of truth; the Otherwise arm recurses into children so unknown node shapes never silently drop sub-analysis (e.g., nested defs inside an unrecognized macro expansion).
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
Input AST is untrusted user source; the Otherwise branch must walk children so attacker-crafted nodes cannot smuggle unanalyzed receive/spawn/send into the program. Every callee returns an Integer status and accumulates errors on analyzer.error_list rather than throwing, so a malformed subtree never aborts a whole-program analysis.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "analyze_elixir_ast" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform semantic analysis of Elixir AST with actor model validation

    Let node_type be proc get_ast_node_type from ast

    Match node_type:
        When AST_MODULE from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_module with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DEFMODULE from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_defmodule with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DEF from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_def with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DEFP from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_defp with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DEFMACRO from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_defmacro with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DEFSTRUCT from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_defstruct with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DEFPROTOCOL from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_defprotocol with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DEFIMPL from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_defimpl with analyzer, ast
        When AST_USE from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_use with analyzer, ast
        When AST_CASE from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_case with analyzer, ast
        When AST_RECEIVE from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_receive with analyzer, ast
        When AST_SPAWN from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_spawn with analyzer, ast
        When AST_SEND from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_send with analyzer, ast
        When AST_GENSERVER_CALL from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_genserver_call with analyzer, ast
        When AST_GENSERVER_CAST from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_genserver_cast with analyzer, ast
        When AST_PATTERN_MATCH from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_pattern_match with analyzer, ast
        When AST_FUNCTION_CALL from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_function_call with analyzer, ast
        When AST_PIPE from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_pipe with analyzer, ast
        When AST_FOR from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_for_comprehension with analyzer, ast
        When AST_WITH from ElixirParser:
            Return proc analyze_with with analyzer, ast
        Otherwise:
            Return proc analyze_children with analyzer, ast
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
defmodule establishes a new lexical and behavioral scope; we save the previous current_module before walking children and restore it after so nested defmodule (Elixir permits this) does not leak state. OTP and supervision validation are deferred to the end so they observe the fully populated function table.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_defmodule" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze Elixir module with OTP behavior detection

    Let module_name be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "name"

    Let elixir_module be a value of type ElixirSemanticModule with
        name as module_name,
        attributes as proc create_dict,
        functions as proc create_dict,
        macros as proc create_dict,
        protocols as proc create_dict,
        implementations as proc create_dict,
        structs as proc create_dict,
        otp_behavior as "",
        supervision_strategy as "",
        dependencies as proc create_list

    Note: Add module to symbol table
    proc add_module_to_scope with analyzer, elixir_module

    Note: Set module context
    Let previous_module be analyzer.current_module
    Set analyzer.current_module to elixir_module

    Note: Analyze module body
    Let child_count be proc get_ast_child_count from ast
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_ast_child with ast, index
        proc analyze_elixir_ast with analyzer, child
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate OTP behavior compliance
    If elixir_module.otp_behavior is not equal to "":
        proc validate_otp_behavior_compliance with analyzer, elixir_module
    End If

    Note: Analyze supervision tree if supervisor
    If elixir_module.supervision_strategy is not equal to "":
        proc analyze_supervision_tree with analyzer, elixir_module
    End If

    Note: Restore previous module context
    Set analyzer.current_module to previous_module

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
def builds an ElixirSemanticFunction record, registers it in the enclosing module before analyzing the body so recursive self-references resolve, and runs validate_pattern_exhaustiveness only after every clause is in the record. The previous_function save/restore mirrors the module case for nested-definition tolerance.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_def" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze Elixir function definition with pattern matching

    Let function_name be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "name"
    Let arity be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "arity"

    Let elixir_function be a value of type ElixirSemanticFunction with
        name as function_name,
        arity as arity,
        clauses as proc create_list,
        guards as proc create_list,
        visibility as "public",
        otp_callback as "",
        pattern_variables as proc create_dict,
        return_patterns as proc create_list,
        side_effects as proc create_list

    Note: Check if this is an OTP callback
    proc check_otp_callback_function with analyzer, elixir_function

    Note: Add function to current module
    proc add_function_to_module with analyzer.current_module, elixir_function

    Note: Set function context
    Let previous_function be analyzer.current_function
    Set analyzer.current_function to elixir_function

    Note: Analyze function clauses
    Let clauses be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "clauses"
    If clauses is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_function_clauses with analyzer, clauses, elixir_function
    End If

    Note: Analyze function body
    Let body be proc get_ast_body from ast
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_function_body with analyzer, body, elixir_function
    End If

    Note: Validate pattern exhaustiveness
    proc validate_pattern_exhaustiveness with analyzer, elixir_function

    Note: Restore previous function context
    Set analyzer.current_function to previous_function

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
case introduces a fresh pattern-binding scope; we swap pattern_context for the duration so bindings made inside the case do not leak to siblings (e.g., {:ok, x} = case ... matches only inside that arm). pattern_coverage is collected across clauses and handed to check_pattern_exhaustiveness so the warning fires once with full information.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_case" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze case expression with pattern matching validation

    Let expr be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "expression"
    proc analyze_elixir_ast with analyzer, expr

    Note: Create new pattern context for case analysis
    Let case_context be proc create_dict
    Let previous_pattern_context be analyzer.pattern_context
    Set analyzer.pattern_context to case_context

    Note: Analyze each case clause
    Let clauses be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "clauses"
    Let pattern_coverage be proc create_list

    If clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let clause_count be proc get_list_size from clauses
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than clause_count:
            Let clause be proc get_list_item with clauses, index
            proc analyze_case_clause with analyzer, clause, pattern_coverage
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Check pattern exhaustiveness
    proc check_pattern_exhaustiveness with analyzer, pattern_coverage, ast

    Note: Restore previous pattern context
    Set analyzer.pattern_context to previous_pattern_context

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
receive is only meaningful inside a process; the context check emits a warning rather than an error because the host process may be set up dynamically (spawn(fn -> receive ... end)). Message patterns are gathered into one list before validate_message_protocol so cross-clause protocol gaps are detected in a single pass.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_receive" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze receive block for actor message handling

    Note: Validate that we're in a process context
    If proc is_in_process_context with analyzer is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_warning with analyzer, "receive block outside process context", ast
    End If

    Note: Analyze message patterns
    Let clauses be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "clauses"
    Let message_patterns be proc create_list

    If clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let clause_count be proc get_list_size from clauses
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than clause_count:
            Let clause be proc get_list_item with clauses, index
            Let pattern be proc get_ast_attribute with clause, "pattern"
            proc analyze_message_pattern with analyzer, pattern, message_patterns
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Validate message protocol compliance
    proc validate_message_protocol with analyzer, message_patterns, ast

    Note: Analyze after clause (timeout)
    Let after_clause be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "after"
    If after_clause is not equal to 0:
        Let timeout be proc get_ast_attribute with after_clause, "timeout"
        proc validate_timeout_expression with analyzer, timeout
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
spawn variants (spawn, spawn_link, spawn_monitor) all share target validation but differ on link/monitor registration; the spawn_type string discriminates them so the actor process record can record the relationship for later supervision-tree analysis. Arity mismatch is an error (not a warning) because OTP processes will crash at startup otherwise.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
The target module/function come from user source; function_exists must be called before recording the spawn so the actor registry never contains references to undefined callables. process_id is generated freshly per spawn to avoid registry-key collisions across analyses.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "analyze_spawn" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze process spawning for actor model validation

    Let spawn_type be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "type"
    Let module_name be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "module"
    Let function_name be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "function"
    Let arguments be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "arguments"

    Note: Validate target function exists and is callable
    If proc function_exists with analyzer, module_name, function_name is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Undefined function in spawn", ast
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Validate arity matches arguments
    Let target_arity be proc get_function_arity with analyzer, module_name, function_name
    Let arg_count be proc get_list_size from arguments
    If target_arity is not equal to arg_count:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Arity mismatch in spawn", ast
    End If

    Note: Create actor process record
    Let actor_process be a value of type ActorProcess with
        spawn_location as ast,
        process_type as spawn_type,
        message_protocol as proc infer_message_protocol with analyzer, module_name, function_name,
        linked_processes as proc create_list,
        monitored_by as proc create_list,
        supervision_info as 0

    Note: Handle linking and monitoring
    If spawn_type is equal to "spawn_link":
        proc add_process_link with analyzer, actor_process
    Otherwise If spawn_type is equal to "spawn_monitor":
        proc add_process_monitor with analyzer, actor_process
    End If

    Note: Register process in actor system
    Let process_id be proc generate_process_id
    proc set_dict_value with analyzer.actor_processes, process_id, actor_process

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
GenServer.call is synchronous; mismatched request shapes against handle_call clauses are the most common Elixir bug, so we resolve the target module and validate the request pattern against its handle_call clauses. Server module resolution may legitimately fail (dynamic Process.whereis), so unknown servers degrade to a warning rather than blocking compilation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_genserver_call" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze GenServer.call for OTP compliance

    Let server be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "server"
    Let request be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "request"
    Let timeout be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "timeout"

    Note: Validate server reference
    proc validate_server_reference with analyzer, server, ast

    Note: Check if server implements GenServer behavior
    Let server_module be proc resolve_server_module with analyzer, server
    If server_module is not equal to "":
        If proc implements_genserver with analyzer, server_module is equal to 0:
            proc add_semantic_warning with analyzer, "Server may not implement GenServer", ast
        End If

        Note: Validate request matches handle_call patterns
        proc validate_genserver_request with analyzer, server_module, request, "handle_call", ast
    End If

    Note: Validate timeout if specified
    If timeout is not equal to 0:
        proc validate_timeout_value with analyzer, timeout, ast
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Elixir's = is a match operator that both tests and binds; we analyze the expression first because pattern reachability depends on what the expression can produce, then collect bindings into a local dict and merge them into pattern_context only after reachability is confirmed so unreachable patterns do not pollute the outer scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_pattern_match" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze pattern matching with variable binding

    Let pattern be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "pattern"
    Let expression be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "expression"

    Note: Analyze expression first
    proc analyze_elixir_ast with analyzer, expression

    Note: Create pattern binding context
    Let pattern_bindings be proc create_dict
    proc analyze_pattern_bindings with analyzer, pattern, pattern_bindings

    Note: Check for unreachable patterns
    proc check_pattern_reachability with analyzer, pattern, ast

    Note: Update pattern context with new bindings
    proc merge_pattern_bindings with analyzer.pattern_context, pattern_bindings

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
use is the macro mechanism by which OTP behaviors are mixed in; we detect well-known behaviors and dispatch to behavior-specific analyzers (each of which knows the contract: GenServer expects handle_call/handle_cast/handle_info, Supervisor expects init/1 returning child specs, etc.). Non-behavior use directives still record a dependency so module-resolution stays complete.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_use" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze use directive for OTP behavior inclusion

    Let module_name be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "module"
    Let options be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "options"

    Note: Check if this is an OTP behavior
    If proc is_otp_behavior with module_name is equal to 1:
        Note: Set OTP behavior for current module
        Set analyzer.current_module.otp_behavior to module_name

        Note: Validate required callbacks will be implemented
        Let required_callbacks be proc get_required_callbacks from module_name
        proc schedule_callback_validation with analyzer, required_callbacks

        Note: Handle behavior-specific analysis
        Match module_name:
            When "GenServer":
                proc analyze_genserver_behavior with analyzer, options, ast
            When "Supervisor":
                proc analyze_supervisor_behavior with analyzer, options, ast
            When "Application":
                proc analyze_application_behavior with analyzer, options, ast
            When "Task":
                proc analyze_task_behavior with analyzer, options, ast
        End Match
    End If

    Note: Add to module dependencies
    proc add_dependency with analyzer.current_module, "use", module_name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
OTP behaviors are contractual: a module declaring `use GenServer` MUST implement every required callback or the BEAM will crash on first message. We loop over the behavior's required-callback table and emit a hard error per missing callback rather than aggregating, so the error messages point users at each individual omission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_otp_behavior_compliance" takes analyzer as Integer, module_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate that module implements required OTP callbacks

    Let behavior be module_info.otp_behavior
    Let required_callbacks be proc get_required_callbacks from behavior
    Let optional_callbacks be proc get_optional_callbacks from behavior

    Note: Check required callbacks
    Let callback_count be proc get_list_size from required_callbacks
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than callback_count:
        Let callback_spec be proc get_list_item with required_callbacks, index
        Let callback_name be proc get_dict_value with callback_spec, "name"
        Let callback_arity be proc get_dict_value with callback_spec, "arity"

        If proc module_has_function with module_info, callback_name, callback_arity is equal to 0:
            proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Missing required callback", module_info
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate callback implementations
    proc validate_callback_implementations with analyzer, module_info, behavior

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Supervisors are validated by extracting child specs from init/1 because the OTP runtime calls exactly that function to bootstrap the tree; absence of init/1 is unrecoverable so we emit an error and return 0. Each child spec is validated individually so a single malformed entry does not mask the rest.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_supervision_tree" takes analyzer as Integer, module_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze supervisor module and build supervision tree

    Let strategy be module_info.supervision_strategy
    Let init_function be proc get_module_function with module_info, "init", 1

    If init_function is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Supervisor missing init/1 function", module_info
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Analyze init function for child specifications
    Let child_specs be proc extract_child_specs with analyzer, init_function

    Note: Validate child specifications
    Let spec_count be proc get_list_size from child_specs
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than spec_count:
        Let child_spec be proc get_list_item with child_specs, index
        proc validate_child_spec with analyzer, child_spec
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Build supervision tree
    Let supervision_node be proc create_supervision_node with module_info, child_specs
    proc set_dict_value with analyzer.supervisor_tree, module_info.name, supervision_node

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The built-in module set is seeded at analyzer construction so user code that references Enum.map or GenServer.start_link never produces spurious "undefined module" errors. Registering OTP behaviors separately (vs. plain modules) lets is_otp_behavior remain a constant-time check.
@End Reasoning
Process called "initialize_elixir_builtins" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Initialize built-in Elixir and OTP modules

    Note: Core Elixir modules
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Kernel"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Enum"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Stream"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "String"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Integer"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Float"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Atom"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Tuple"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "List"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Map"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Process"

    Note: OTP behaviors
    proc add_otp_behavior with analyzer, "GenServer"
    proc add_otp_behavior with analyzer, "Supervisor"
    proc add_otp_behavior with analyzer, "Application"
    proc add_otp_behavior with analyzer, "Task"
    proc add_otp_behavior with analyzer, "Agent"

    Note: OTP applications
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Registry"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "DynamicSupervisor"
    proc add_builtin_module with analyzer, "Task.Supervisor"

    Return 1
End Process

Note: Helper processes for Elixir semantic analysis

@Reasoning:
Errors are recorded as structured dicts (message + line + column + severity) so the downstream diagnostics formatter can sort and group them; storing severity alongside the message keeps a single error_list capable of holding both errors and warnings if needed, while the dedicated warning_list keeps the two streams separable at the source.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as String, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add semantic error with location information

    Let error be a value of type Dictionary[String, Any] with
        "message" as message,
        "line" as proc get_ast_line with ast,
        "column" as proc get_ast_column with ast,
        "severity" as "error"

    proc add_to_list with analyzer.error_list, error
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warnings have the same shape as errors but go to a separate list so callers can choose to suppress them without losing error semantics. Severity is still recorded inside the dict to keep individual records self-describing for downstream consumers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_semantic_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, message as String, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add semantic warning with location information

    Let warning be a value of type Dictionary[String, Any] with
        "message" as message,
        "line" as proc get_ast_line with ast,
        "column" as proc get_ast_column with ast,
        "severity" as "warning"

    proc add_to_list with analyzer.warning_list, warning
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The five canonical OTP behaviors are hard-coded because they're a closed set defined by OTP itself; using Match instead of a dict lookup keeps the test branch-free and is the natural shape for a fixed enumeration. Otherwise returns 0 (false) so user modules cannot impersonate a behavior by name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_otp_behavior" takes module_name as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if module is an OTP behavior

    Match module_name:
        When "GenServer": Return 1
        When "Supervisor": Return 1
        When "Application": Return 1
        When "Task": Return 1
        When "Agent": Return 1
        Otherwise: Return 0
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each OTP behavior declares a minimum-viable callback set: GenServer needs init/1 (handle_* are optional in the BEAM but typically required in practice), Supervisor needs init/1, Application needs start/2. We deliberately list only the truly-required callbacks so validate_otp_behavior_compliance doesn't false-positive on minimal but valid implementations.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_required_callbacks" takes behavior as String returns Integer:
    Note: Get required callbacks for OTP behavior

    Match behavior:
        When "GenServer":
            Let callbacks be proc create_list
            proc add_callback_spec with callbacks, "init", 1
            Return callbacks
        When "Supervisor":
            Set callbacks to proc create_list
            proc add_callback_spec with callbacks, "init", 1
            Return callbacks
        When "Application":
            Set callbacks to proc create_list
            proc add_callback_spec with callbacks, "start", 2
            Return callbacks
        Otherwise:
            Return proc create_list
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
A function is considered to exist iff its enclosing module is in the symbol table AND the module's functions dict contains the function name; we short-circuit on missing module so the dict_contains call is never invoked against a null pointer. Arity is intentionally not checked here because spawn-site validation handles arity separately.
@End Reasoning
Process called "function_exists" takes analyzer as Integer, module_name as String, function_name as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if function exists in module

    Let module_info be proc get_dict_value with analyzer.symbol_table, module_name
    If module_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc dict_contains with module_info.functions, function_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
GenServer membership is determined by the otp_behavior field set during analyze_use, not by any structural pattern (a module can implement handle_call without `use GenServer`, but the OTP runtime won't treat it as a GenServer). String equality on the behavior tag therefore matches the BEAM's own membership test.
@End Reasoning
Process called "implements_genserver" takes analyzer as Integer, module_name as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if module implements GenServer behavior

    Let module_info be proc get_dict_value with analyzer.symbol_table, module_name
    If module_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return module_info.otp_behavior is equal to "GenServer"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The dictionary stores keys/values plus a size counter; 24 bytes is the analyzer-local convention for the header (three 8-byte slots) before any entries are appended via set_dict_value, keeping construction O(1) and decoupling from the dict implementation's growth policy.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_dict" returns Integer:
    Note: Create dictionary for storage
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
The list header is two 8-byte slots (data pointer + size) which the list operations grow on demand; allocating just the header here keeps the analyzer's many empty lists (warning_list when there are no warnings, etc.) cheap.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_list" returns Integer:
    Note: Create list for storage
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Errors are exposed via accessor rather than direct field access so the analyzer remains free to switch its internal representation (e.g., to a deduplicated set) without changing the consumer contract.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_semantic_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return list of semantic errors
    Return analyzer.error_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warning access mirrors error access so callers using a single iterator pattern can swap streams without code changes; both lists share the same record shape established in add_semantic_error/add_semantic_warning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_semantic_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return list of semantic warnings
    Return analyzer.warning_list
End Process